CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, September 1, 1956, pg. 1, reads: "What About This? - Objecting citizens, who no longer sport a family 'coat-of-arms,' consisting of a cotton patch with bandana rampant, complained that the stereotyped name of this street in East Liberty, 'Rastus Way' (left photo), is an insult and should be changed...The dirt alley, which was named in 1910, while other residences face nicely-kept Julius St. 'Rastus Way' has no place in a city which brags about its 'New Look' and general renaissance program.  The name should be changed. Don't you think? - Harris Photos."
TitMainTitle: Two story dark asphalt brick home with light colored trim, at corner of Frankstown Avenue and Rastus Way, East Liberty
